No, it was written by God, it says so.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>All Scripture is God-breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting and training in righteousness, so that the man of God may be thoroughly equipped for every good work.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Now He wrote His words through humans, but God wrote the Bible, they are His words.  They are not the words of men.  And we know what books were written by Him in that there is no contradiction between them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Without the Apostolic Tradition there would have been no way to pick among the various writings.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
As I said before, I believe God is fully capable of revealing to man what His word is and isn't.  This Apostolic Tradition looks like putting to much faith and trust in man.  And it makes Christianity sound too much like any other world religion.  I don't put my faith and trust in man, I put my faith and trust in an all powerful God who is fully capable of revealing Himself to us and revealing His word to us.<br>
<br>
And something to consider - the protestant movement may very well have been God's doing because He didn't like what He was seeing in catholocism.  It wouldn't be the first time that religious leaders were claiming to be doing the will and work of God when in God's eyes they weren't.  Just a possibility to consider.  Because Jesus was considered highly unorthodox by the religious leaders of His day as were the early Christians - Paul especially who was raised in their orthodox ways.  And who was it that had considered the Old Testament books to be scripture back in Jesus day?  The established Jewish religious leaders (can't remember what they were called). <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
