I think a distinction has to be made between Jewish oral tradition which rejected Christ, and the Christian Tradition...as <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>James Bernstein</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> wrote:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>..the same God who speaks to us through His written Word, the Bible, spoke also through the Apostles of Christ as they taught and preached in person.  The Scriptures themselves teach in this passage (and others) that this oral tradition is what we are to keep!  Written and oral tradition are not in conflict, but are parts of one whole.  This explains why the Fathers teach that he who does not have the Church as his Mother does not have God as his Father.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
